#. REF: sc1
msgctxt "an10.91:1.1"
msgid "Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme. "
msgstr "At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery. "

msgctxt "an10.91:1.2"
msgid "Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ bhagavā etadavoca: "
msgstr "Then the householder Anāthapiṇḍika went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. Seated to one side, the Buddha said to the householder Anāthapiṇḍika: "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: pts-vp-pli5.177, sc2
msgctxt "an10.91:2.1"
msgid "“Dasayime, gahapati, kāmabhogī santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ. "
msgstr "“These ten pleasure seekers are found in the world. "

msgctxt "an10.91:2.2"
msgid "Katame dasa? "
msgstr "What ten? "

# NOTE: Sahasa is related to the root for “power”, and the meaning “violent” is secondary (if indeed it applies at all in the Pali). It seems to me that it would include any business practices that involved intimidation, threats, or merely leveraging market position in unskillful ways. So I prefer coercion to BB’s violence.
msgctxt "an10.91:2.3"
msgid "Idha, gahapati, ekacco kāmabhogī adhammena bhoge pariyesati sāhasena; "
msgstr "First, a pleasure seeker seeks wealth using illegitimate, coercive means. "

